  <content>
    <title>Vector Database Development Setup</title>

    <summary>Spin up any major vector database (Qdrant, Weaviate, Milvus, pgvector, Pinecone, Chroma) locally via Docker one-liners or pip install, connect a Python client, create a collection, and verify the stack is functional before writing pipeline code.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Starting with a running, verified local database eliminates a common failure class in RAG development: bugs that appear to be pipeline logic errors but are actually misconfigured connections, wrong dimension sizes, or missing indexes. A five-minute local setup gives a true integration baseline against which embedding and retrieval code can be tested deterministically.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new RAG pipeline and need a vector store to develop against.</item>
        <item>Evaluating a database before committing to a production deployment.</item>
        <item>Running integration tests that require a real (not mocked) vector database.</item>
        <item>Migrating from Chroma in-memory to a persistent database during prototyping.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Proof-of-concept with fewer than 10K documents — use Chroma in-memory or pgvector on an existing Postgres; no Docker needed.</item>
        <item>Production deployment — use the vector-db-setup-prod methodology instead; dev defaults are not hardened.</item>
        <item>The bottleneck is embedding quality or chunking strategy — fix those upstream before adding database complexity.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="quickstart-commands">
      <p>Quickest path to a running database per engine:</p>

      <section name="qdrant-docker">
        <rule>
          <statement>Start Qdrant for development with a single docker run command exposing HTTP (6333) and gRPC (6334) ports; mount a volume for persistence so data survives container restarts.</statement>
          <rationale>Without a persistent volume, all indexed vectors are lost on restart, making iterative development painful.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <example type="good" title="Qdrant development container with persistence">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
docker run -d --name qdrant \
  -p 6333:6333 \
  -p 6334:6334 \
  -v $(pwd)/qdrant_storage:/qdrant/storage:z \
  qdrant/qdrant:latest

# Verify
curl http://localhost:6333/readyz
]]></code>
        </example>

        <example type="good" title="Qdrant with custom config (disable telemetry, set gRPC port)">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
docker run -d --name qdrant \
  -p 6333:6333 \
  -p 6334:6334 \
  -v $(pwd)/qdrant_storage:/qdrant/storage:z \
  -v $(pwd)/qdrant_config.yaml:/qdrant/config/production.yaml:ro \
  -e QDRANT__SERVICE__GRPC_PORT=6334 \
  -e QDRANT__TELEMETRY_DISABLED=true \
  qdrant/qdrant:latest
]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="weaviate-docker">
        <example type="good" title="Weaviate development container">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
docker run -d --name weaviate \
  -p 8080:8080 \
  -p 50051:50051 \
  -v weaviate_data:/var/lib/weaviate \
  -e AUTHENTICATION_ANONYMOUS_ACCESS_ENABLED=true \
  -e PERSISTENCE_DATA_PATH=/var/lib/weaviate \
  -e QUERY_DEFAULTS_LIMIT=25 \
  -e DEFAULT_VECTORIZER_MODULE=none \
  semitechnologies/weaviate:latest

# Verify
curl http://localhost:8080/v1/.well-known/ready
]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="milvus-docker">
        <example type="good" title="Milvus standalone via official script">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
curl -sfL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/milvus-io/milvus/master/scripts/standalone_embed.sh \
  -o standalone_embed.sh

bash standalone_embed.sh start

# Verify
curl http://localhost:9091/healthz
]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="pgvector-docker">
        <example type="good" title="pgvector container with extension pre-enabled">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
docker run -d --name pgvector \
  -p 5432:5432 \
  -e POSTGRES_USER=vectordb \
  -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=vectordb \
  -e POSTGRES_DB=vectors \
  -v pgvector_data:/var/lib/postgresql/data \
  pgvector/pgvector:pg16

# Enable extension
docker exec -it pgvector psql -U vectordb -d vectors \
  -c "CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS vector;"

# Verify version
docker exec -it pgvector psql -U vectordb -d vectors \
  -c "SELECT extversion FROM pg_extension WHERE extname = 'vector';"
]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="chroma-docker">
        <example type="good" title="Chroma server with persistence (prototyping only)">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
docker run -d --name chroma \
  -p 8000:8000 \
  -v chroma_data:/chroma/chroma \
  -e IS_PERSISTENT=TRUE \
  -e ANONYMIZED_TELEMETRY=FALSE \
  chromadb/chroma:latest

# Verify
curl http://localhost:8000/api/v1/heartbeat
]]></code>
          <note>Chroma is primarily for prototyping. For production, migrate to Qdrant, Weaviate, or another production-grade database.</note>
        </example>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="client-connections">
      <p>Python client connection patterns for each database:</p>

      <example type="good" title="Qdrant client — local and cloud">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from qdrant_client import QdrantClient

# Local development
client = QdrantClient(host="localhost", port=6333)

# With gRPC (recommended for production)
client = QdrantClient(
    host="localhost",
    port=6334,
    prefer_grpc=True,
)

# Cloud/remote with API key
client = QdrantClient(
    url="https://your-cluster.qdrant.io",
    api_key="your-api-key",
)

# Verify
print(client.get_collections())
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Weaviate client — local and cloud">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import weaviate
from weaviate.classes.init import Auth

# Local development
client = weaviate.connect_to_local()

# Cloud connection
client = weaviate.connect_to_weaviate_cloud(
    cluster_url="https://your-cluster.weaviate.cloud",
    auth_credentials=Auth.api_key("your-api-key"),
)

# Custom connection (explicit host/port)
client = weaviate.connect_to_custom(
    http_host="localhost",
    http_port=8080,
    http_secure=False,
    grpc_host="localhost",
    grpc_port=50051,
    grpc_secure=False,
)

print(client.is_ready())
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Milvus client">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from pymilvus import MilvusClient

# Simple client (local file — Milvus Lite)
client = MilvusClient("milvus_demo.db")

# Connect to server
client = MilvusClient(
    uri="http://localhost:19530",
    token="root:Milvus",
)

print(client.list_collections())
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="pgvector connection">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import psycopg2
from pgvector.psycopg2 import register_vector

conn = psycopg2.connect(
    "postgresql://vectordb:vectordb@localhost:5432/vectors"
)
register_vector(conn)

# Verify extension
cur = conn.cursor()
cur.execute("SELECT extversion FROM pg_extension WHERE extname = 'vector';")
print(cur.fetchone())
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Chroma client">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import chromadb

# In-memory (ephemeral)
client = chromadb.Client()

# Persistent storage
client = chromadb.PersistentClient(path="./chroma_db")

# Remote server
client = chromadb.HttpClient(host="localhost", port=8000)

print(client.list_collections())
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Pinecone client">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from pinecone import Pinecone, ServerlessSpec

pc = Pinecone(api_key="your-api-key")

# Create serverless index
pc.create_index(
    name="my-index",
    dimension=1536,
    metric="cosine",
    spec=ServerlessSpec(
        cloud="aws",
        region="us-east-1",
    ),
)

index = pc.Index("my-index")
print(index.describe_index_stats())
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="collection-setup">
      <p>Create a collection with correct dimensions, distance metric, and basic indexes before inserting any vectors.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Create payload/metadata indexes on filter fields (category, source, date) at collection creation time, not after data load. Qdrant requires explicit payload index creation; pgvector requires a separate CREATE INDEX; Weaviate uses indexFilterable property flags.</statement>
        <rationale>Adding indexes after data load on large collections forces a full scan rebuild, which blocks queries and takes hours at scale.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Qdrant collection with HNSW, quantization, and payload indexes">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from qdrant_client import QdrantClient
from qdrant_client.models import (
    VectorParams, Distance,
    HnswConfigDiff, OptimizersConfigDiff,
    ScalarQuantization, ScalarQuantizationConfig,
    PayloadSchemaType,
)

client = QdrantClient(host="localhost", port=6333)

client.create_collection(
    collection_name="documents",
    vectors_config=VectorParams(
        size=1536,
        distance=Distance.COSINE,
    ),
    hnsw_config=HnswConfigDiff(
        m=16,
        ef_construct=100,
    ),
    optimizers_config=OptimizersConfigDiff(
        indexing_threshold=20000,
    ),
    on_disk_payload=True,  # store large payloads on disk
)

# Create payload indexes for faster filtering
client.create_payload_index(
    collection_name="documents",
    field_name="category",
    field_schema=PayloadSchemaType.KEYWORD,
)
client.create_payload_index(
    collection_name="documents",
    field_name="page",
    field_schema=PayloadSchemaType.INTEGER,
)
client.create_payload_index(
    collection_name="documents",
    field_name="created_at",
    field_schema=PayloadSchemaType.DATETIME,
)

info = client.get_collection("documents")
print(f"Created collection with {info.vectors_count} vectors")
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Weaviate collection (BYOV, HNSW)">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import weaviate
from weaviate.classes.config import Configure, Property, DataType, VectorDistances

client = weaviate.connect_to_local()

documents = client.collections.create(
    name="Document",
    vectorizer_config=Configure.Vectorizer.none(),
    properties=[
        Property(name="text", data_type=DataType.TEXT),
        Property(name="source", data_type=DataType.TEXT),
        Property(name="page", data_type=DataType.INT),
        Property(
            name="category",
            data_type=DataType.TEXT,
            skip_vectorization=True,
        ),
        Property(name="created_at", data_type=DataType.DATE),
    ],
    vector_index_config=Configure.VectorIndex.hnsw(
        ef=100,
        max_connections=16,
        distance_metric=VectorDistances.COSINE,
    ),
)
print(f"Created collection: {documents.name}")
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="pgvector table with HNSW index">
        <code lang="sql"><![CDATA[
-- Enable extension (PostgreSQL 14+)
CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS vector;

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS documents (
    id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    text TEXT NOT NULL,
    source VARCHAR(255),
    page INTEGER,
    category VARCHAR(100),
    embedding vector(1536),
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
);

-- HNSW index — always prefer over IVFFlat for production
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS documents_embedding_idx
    ON documents USING hnsw (embedding vector_cosine_ops)
    WITH (m = 16, ef_construction = 64);

-- Metadata indexes for filtered queries
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS documents_category_idx ON documents(category);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS documents_source_idx ON documents(source);
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="dev-checklist">
      <checklist>
        <check>Docker installed and running; port conflicts checked (6333, 6334, 8080, 19530, 5432).</check>
        <check>Database container started; health endpoint returns 200.</check>
        <check>Python SDK installed and version is compatible with the server.</check>
        <check>Collection created with correct dimensions and distance metric.</check>
        <check>Payload/metadata indexes created for all filter fields.</check>
        <check>Sample vectors inserted and queried — results returned correctly.</check>
        <check>Data survives a container restart (volume mount confirmed).</check>
        <check>API keys and connection strings in .env file, not hardcoded.</check>
        <check>Different configs used for dev, test, prod environments.</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <p>Agentic workflow notes: vector DB setup is a one-time infrastructure task. The agent reads the target database selection from config, provisions the service (Docker or managed API), creates the schema/collection, and verifies the connection. Downstream RAG agents consume the validated connection config.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Agents MUST handle the "collection already exists" case gracefully — `recreate_collection` drops all data. Use a get-or-create pattern: check for existence first, create only if absent.</statement>
        <rationale>Idempotent provisioning is required for agents that may run setup steps multiple times (retry, re-run, pipeline restart).</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Calling recreate_collection unconditionally on every agent run.</description>
        <reason>Drops existing data silently. Always check collection existence and skip creation if already present.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using Chroma in-memory for anything beyond single-session prototyping.</description>
        <reason>Data is lost on process exit. Use PersistentClient or migrate to Qdrant/pgvector once the pipeline is past initial exploration.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

